\f1\b\fs48 \cf0 Stylometric Profile of the Author\'92s Outgoing Messages (2011\'962025)\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\fs36 \cf0 Lexical Usage Patterns\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Core Vocabulary and Diction:
\f0\b0  The author\'92s texts are dominated by first- and second-person pronouns (\'93I\'94, \'93you\'94, \'93u\'94), conveying a personal, conversational tone. Common function words like \'93just,\'94 \'93like,\'94 and \'93so\'94 are used heavily as discourse fillers and intensifiers. For example, 
\f1\b \'93I don't wanna sound clingy just like I really wasn't upset\'94
\f0\b0  shows \'93just\'94 and \'93like\'94 employed to soften and qualify a statement. The word 
\f1\b \'93just\'94
\f0\b0  appears very frequently to downplay assertions or introduce explanations (e.g. 
\f1\b \'93Srsly I'll just keep doing this forever\'94
\f0\b0 ). Similarly, 
\f1\b \'93like\'94
\f0\b0  is often inserted in a colloquial manner (e.g. 
\f1\b \'93Ah I feel so bad and like I sounded weird\'94
\f0\b0 ), reflecting a spontaneous, speech-like quality in the messaging. The author\'92s core lexicon also includes many affectionate terms and pet names, especially in romantic contexts (calling someone \'93sweetest,\'94 \'93b,\'94 \'93bb\'94 for baby, etc.), as in 
\f1\b \'93Hiiii bb I miss you so much\'94
\f0\b0 . Overall, the diction is informal, emotive, and heavily oriented around personal feelings and relationship dynamics (
\f1\b \'93I love you so much\'94
\f0\b0  is a recurring sentiment).\

\f1\b Slang and Abbreviations:
\f0\b0  The author liberally uses internet and texting slang. Laughter and interjections are commonly rendered as 
\f1\b \'93lol\'94
\f0\b0 , 
\f1\b \'93LOL\'94
\f0\b0 , or extended forms like 
\f1\b \'93lololol\'94
\f0\b0  (multiple lols) to indicate amusement (e.g. 
\f1\b \'93There he goes lololol\'94
\f0\b0 ). Similarly, 
\f1\b \'93lmao\'94
\f0\b0 /\'93LMAO\'94 emerges in later years (e.g. 
\f1\b \'93Lmao well then why did you even tell me about it\'94
\f0\b0  in 2023) alongside 
\f1\b \'93haha\'94
\f0\b0  variations (
\f1\b \'93Hahaha I know I'm just trying to cover all my bases\'94
\f0\b0 ). Common chat acronyms appear throughout: 
\f1\b \'93omg\'94
\f0\b0  for shock or excitement (
\f1\b \'93Omg you're the sweetest\'94
\f0\b0 ), 
\f1\b \'93idk\'94
\f0\b0  (\'93I don\'92t know\'94) and 
\f1\b \'93idc\'94
\f0\b0  (\'93I don\'92t care\'94) for uncertainty or indifference (
\f1\b \'93Or something idk idc\'94
\f0\b0 ), 
\f1\b \'93wtf\'94
\f0\b0  for disbelief (
\f1\b \'93Yeah wtf!! B my belly hurts sooo bad\'94
\f0\b0 ), and 
\f1\b \'93btw\'94
\f0\b0  (\'93by the way\'94) for asides (
\f1\b \'93Btw if you at any point wanna golf just let me know\'94
\f0\b0 ). Pronouns and articles are often clipped to single letters \'96 using 
\f1\b \'93u\'94
\f0\b0  for you and 
\f1\b \'93ur\'94
\f0\b0  for your \'96 especially in quick messages (
\f1\b \'93Here u go\'85 Ur welcome\'94
\f0\b0 ). The author also employs 
\f1\b \'93gonna\'94
\f0\b0  (going to) and 
\f1\b \'93wanna\'94
\f0\b0  (want to) in place of formal phrases (
\f1\b \'93I'm gonna call you\'94
\f0\b0 , 
\f1\b \'93What do you wanna do\'94
\f0\b0 ), reinforcing the casual register. This consistent use of contemporary slang and abbreviations gives the messages an easy, colloquial flow.\

\f1\b Intensifiers and Emphasis:
\f0\b0  Exaggerated language is a hallmark of the style. The author frequently elongates words for emphasis \'96 especially intensifiers like 
\f2\i so
\f0\i0 , 
\f2\i too
\f0\i0 , 
\f2\i way
\f0\i0  \'96 by repeating letters. For instance, 
\f2\i \'93so\'94
\f0\i0  becomes 
\f1\b \'93sooooo\'94
\f0\b0  to intensify happiness or frustration (
\f1\b \'93I'm sooooo happy that we're one step closer\'94
\f0\b0 ), and 
\f2\i \'93way\'94
\f0\i0  becomes 
\f1\b \'93waaaay\'94
\f0\b0  to stress degree (
\f1\b \'93you are waaaay smarter than you let on\'94
\f0\b0 ). This occurs with emotional expressions as well, e.g. 
\f1\b \'93I suuuuck\'94
\f0\b0  or 
\f1\b \'93gooooo\'94
\f0\b0  (for \'93go\'94) when whining or begging. The author also uses all-caps words or phrases as intensifiers in informal contexts, effectively \'93shouting\'94 certain words for emphasis. For example, 
\f1\b \'93U A BAD BITCH\'94
\f0\b0  (in playful praise) or 
\f1\b \'93Do you not see how FUCKING TERRIBLE you are making me look\'94
\f0\b0  (in genuine anger) demonstrate how capitalization is used to amplify tone. Another favorite intensifier is 
\f1\b \'93literally\'94
\f0\b0 , which the author often inserts for hyperbole or emphasis, sometimes humorously. In emotional statements we see it used earnestly (if not 
\f2\i literally
\f0\i0  accurately) as in 
\f1\b \'93there literally aren't enough hours in the day to explain how much I love you\'94
\f0\b0 , whereas in lighter moments the author even pokes fun at themselves for overusing it (
\f1\b \'93I mean yes you literally are\'85 And yes you figuratively are as well lol\'94
\f0\b0 ). Overall, the lexicon is 
\f1\b highly expressive
\f0\b0 , relying on lengthened spellings, all-caps, and emphatic adverbs to convey intensity.\

\f1\b Profanity and Vulgar Slang:
\f0\b0  The author is very free with profanity, using it both for emphasis and humor. 
\f1\b \'93Fuck\'94
\f0\b0  (and variants like 
\f2\i fucking
\f0\i0 ) is one of the most frequently used strong words in their messages. It appears as a blunt expletive (
\f1\b \'93Fuckfuckfuck I even love your name\'94
\f0\b0 ), an intensifier (
\f1\b \'93need to make damn fucking sure you understand\'94
\f0\b0 ), or a verb for literal scenarios (
\f1\b \'93we can fuck in front of her for all I care\'94
\f0\b0 ). They also use 
\f2\i fuck
\f0\i0  in a drawn-out or repeated manner for dramatic effect (typing 
\f1\b \'93Fuckkkkkkkkk\'94
\f0\b0  with multiple \'91k\'92s in excitement or frustration). 
\f1\b \'93Shit\'94
\f0\b0  is similarly common, often in idiomatic phrases: 
\f2\i the shit
\f0\i0  to mean \'93the best\'94 (
\f1\b \'93She's THE SHIT\'94
\f0\b0  as high praise), 
\f2\i holy shit
\f0\i0  to express surprise (
\f1\b \'93holy shit if it\'92s right\'94
\f0\b0 ), and \'93shit\'94 as a generic noun for things or nonsense (
\f1\b \'93Is she still saying shit to you\'94
\f0\b0 ). The texts also feature 
\f1\b \'93bitch\'94
\f0\b0  in various uses. Sometimes it\'92s clearly derogatory or insulting, but the author also uses 
\f2\i bitch
\f0\i0  playfully or self-deprecatingly. For example, he jokingly calls his partner 
\f1\b \'93my ratchet ass bitch\'94
\f0\b0  while simultaneously expressing affection (
\f1\b \'93That's you\'85 And I love ya to Pluto and back\'94
\f0\b0 ). In another message he mockingly refers to himself as 
\f1\b \'93a little pussy bitch about illness! 
\f3\b0 \uc0\u55357 \u56859 
\f1\b \'94
\f0\b0  to convey self-effacing humor about his sensitivity. Other crude terms like 
\f1\b \'93asshole\'94
\f0\b0  appear especially when venting about third parties (
\f1\b \'93she\'92s an asshole, just trying to get in my head\'94
\f0\b0 ) or teasing close friends (
\f1\b \'93You ASSHOLE\'85 LOL I know\'94
\f0\b0 ). In sum, profanity is a 
\f1\b normalized part of the author\'92s lexicon
\f0\b0 , used without hesitation. The frequent use of \'93fuck,\'94 \'93shit,\'94 and \'93bitch\'94 \'97 even in affectionate contexts \'97 suggests a communication style that is candid, unfiltered, and at ease with vulgarity for effect. Despite the crudeness, these words often carry a 
\f1\b friendly or cathartic tone
\f0\b0  in context, aligning with the author\'92s overall blunt and passionate voice.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Morphosyntactic Characteristics\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Sentence Structure and Length:
\f0\b0  The author\'92s messages tend toward 
\f1\b short, simple sentence structures
\f0\b0 , often representing a single clause or thought per text bubble. Many messages are sentence fragments or a few words, reflecting how one might speak in quick bursts. For example, the author often breaks a multi-clause thought into successive messages: 
\f1\b \'93She's still...here....ughhhh\'94
\f0\b0  (first message) then 
\f1\b \'93Can I like...tell her?\'94
\f0\b0  (follow-up message seconds later). Each text on its own is a fragment, but together they form a complete idea. This fragmentary delivery gives the conversation a 
\f1\b stream-of-consciousness feel
\f0\b0 , as if we are seeing each thought as it occurs. When sentences are longer, they are usually strung together with simple conjunctions (\'93and\'94, \'93but\'94) or ellipses rather than formal complex syntax. For instance, 
\f1\b \'93But I just like...ah...this feels so important and if I need to explain like why I was sad before and happy now...\'94
\f0\b0  uses multiple conjunctions and pauses (\'93...\'94) instead of breaking into separate sentences or using semicolons. The result is a run-on quality that mirrors spoken language. There is little evidence of structured, multi-clause sentences with subordination; instead, the author often sends a 
\f1\b rapid series of short clauses
\f0\b0  in separate texts rather than embedding them in one long sentence.\

\f1\b Contractions and Colloquial Forms:
\f0\b0  The author nearly always uses 
\f1\b contracted forms
\f0\b0  (I'm, you're, can't, it's) instead of full formal words, in line with the informal style. For example, 
\f1\b \'93I\'92m not gonna lie\'94
\f0\b0 , 
\f1\b \'93you\'92re perfect\'94
\f0\b0 , 
\f1\b \'93it\'92s gonna be fine\'94
\f0\b0  are typical (many instances occur, e.g. 
\f1\b \'93Okay I'm walking into the house now. Gonna hide phone so it doesn't get broked\'94
\f0\b0 ). In fact, the texts sometimes use even more colloquial contractions beyond standard English: 
\f1\b \'93ima\'94
\f0\b0  (or \'93I\'92ma\'94) is used for 
\f2\i \'93I\'92m gonna\'94
\f0\i0  \'96 as in 
\f1\b \'93Here's what ima do\'94
\f0\b0  \'96 and 
\f1\b \'93whatcha\'94
\f0\b0  appears for 
\f2\i \'93what are you\'94
\f0\i0  (e.g. 
\f1\b \'93Whatcha dooooin\'94
\f0\b0  for \'93what are you doing\'94). The author also writes 
\f1\b \'93\'92em\'94
\f0\b0  for 
\f2\i them
\f0\i0  occasionally and 
\f1\b \'93ya\'94
\f0\b0  for 
\f2\i you
\f0\i0  (see 
\f1\b \'93If ya know what's good for ya\'94
\f0\b0 ). These non-standard contractions and phonetic spellings (like 
\f2\i \'93tryna\'94
\f0\i0  for trying to, 
\f2\i \'93kinda\'94
\f0\i0  for kind of, 
\f2\i \'93gonna\'94
\f0\i0 , 
\f2\i \'93wanna\'94
\f0\i0 , etc.) are prevalent, giving the text an 
\f2\i authentically spoken
\f0\i0  flavor. Standard grammar rules are loosened in favor of phonetic ease \'96 for example, the author says 
\f1\b \'93I told you that i totally understand\'94
\f0\b0 , leaving \'93I\'94 in lowercase \'93i\'94 mid-sentence, likely due to fast typing or disabled auto-correct. Such lowercase 
\f1\b \'93i\'94
\f0\b0  for the pronoun appears occasionally (perhaps uncorrected in the rush of messaging), though mostly \'93I\'94 is capitalized. There\'92s also inconsistent agreement and dropped words in some sentences, suggesting an 
\f2\i impromptu quality
\f0\i0  where the author is typing as thoughts come, sometimes neglecting minor grammatical consistency. Despite these quirks, the overall syntax remains clear \'96 the author relies on 
\f2\i simple clauses, conversational connectors, and common contractions
\f0\i0  to communicate fluidly.\

\f1\b Use of Questions and Commands:
\f0\b0  The author frequently poses questions, often in a rapid or rhetorical manner, and these are usually 
\f1\b informally structured
\f0\b0 . It\'92s common to see multiple question marks or combined punctuation for emphasis in questions (e.g. 
\f1\b \'93how can you tell?!?!\'94
\f0\b0  showing excitement and inquiry together). Yes/no questions are often truncated: 
\f1\b \'93Where atttt?\'94
\f0\b0  (with 
\f2\i \'93at\'94
\f0\i0  extended for emphasis) or 
\f1\b \'93You wanna bail or stay here?\'94
\f0\b0  \'96 dropping the subject in the second clause. Commands and suggestions are phrased casually, often starting with \'93let\'92s\'94 or expressed as friendly imperatives: 
\f1\b \'93Meet me at marathon\'94
\f0\b0  or 
\f1\b \'93Just let me know and I will always be there\'94
\f0\b0 . The tone is invitational rather than authoritative, aligning with the cooperative, affectionate context of most messages.\

\f1\b Grammar and Negation:
\f0\b0  The texts show a preference for 
\f1\b informal negation
\f0\b0 . The author almost never uses \'93do not\'94 or \'93cannot,\'94 opting instead for 
\f1\b \'93don\'92t,\'94 \'93can\'92t,\'94 \'93won\'92t,\'94 \'93ain\'92t\'94
\f0\b0  etc. In fact, double negatives or colloquial negation slip in occasionally for effect: 
\f2\i \'93that shit ain\'92t no jokes\'94
\f0\i0 . Grammar \'93mistakes\'94 that are typical in speech are present, though they seem intentional or at least not corrected \'96 for example, 
\f1\b \'93If I faint just revive me and keep going\'94
\f0\b0  (missing a comma before \'93just\'94 as it\'92s a spoken run-on), or 
\f1\b \'93My heart hurts from not seeing you\'85 How long do u think you\'92ll be out for?\'94
\f0\b0  ending a clause with a preposition (\'93out for\'94). These lend authenticity to the conversational style. The author does not appear concerned with formal grammar rules like not ending sentences with prepositions or using whom vs. who, etc. The messaging grammar is 
\f1\b driven by clarity and emotion, not formality
\f0\b0 . When needed, the author can produce grammatically complex sentences \'96 for instance, when writing a serious missive, they managed a fully structured sentence: 
\f1\b \'93I\'92ve been trying really hard not to send you any emotionally loaded texts while you\'92re working.\'94
\f0\b0 . But such sentences stand out as deliberate and likely composed with extra care, whereas the bulk of the corpus favors 
\f2\i simple, loosely connected syntax
\f0\i0 . In summary, the morphosyntactic profile is one of 
\f1\b simplicity and speech-mimicking structure
\f0\b0 : short clauses, heavy use of contractions, colloquial shorthand, and grammar that bends toward expressive ease rather than textbook rules.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Orthographic and Punctuation Style\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Capitalization:
\f0\b0  In general, the author uses standard capitalization for the start of sentences and the pronoun \'93I\'94 \'96 but with plenty of 
\f2\i intentional deviations
\f0\i0 . They sometimes leave \'93I\'94 lowercase in mid-sentence (as noted earlier, 
\f1\b \'93i totally understand\'94
\f0\b0 ), likely out of typing haste. More conspicuously, the author employs 
\f1\b all-caps
\f0\b0  text strategically to convey strong emotion such as excitement, anger, or joking mock-seriousness. All-caps may be used for single words or short phrases: e.g., 
\f1\b \'93YOU? BEER?\'94
\f0\b0  to playfully emphasize a suggestion, or 
\f1\b \'93MOM NO\'94
\f0\b0  to mimic a shouted protest. In conflicts, they turn whole clauses caps-lock: 
\f1\b \'93For NO REASON\'94
\f0\b0  shows rage and exasperation by capitalizing the key phrase. This selective all-caps usage is a form of 
\f1\b textual prosody
\f0\b0 , indicating how the author would likely raise their voice or stress those words in speech. Conversely, there are moments of all-lowercase usage beyond just the stray \'93i\'94 \'96 particularly in later messages where the author\'92s tone is subdued or resigned. For example, 
\f1\b \'93i\'92m not about to give that up now lol\'94
\f0\b0  is typed all-lowercase (aside from LOL), perhaps reflecting a tired or nonchalant voice in that moment. These shifts suggest the author sometimes toggles off capitalization to match a mood (lowercase for deadpan or somber delivery, uppercase for intensity). Overall, capitalization is 
\f1\b not rigidly applied
\f0\b0  \'96 it\'92s manipulated for tone, with correctness sacrificed occasionally for speed or style.\

\f1\b Punctuation Use:
\f0\b0  The author\'92s punctuation is expressive and non-formal. Standard periods and commas are used, but often omitted at the ends of messages \'96 it\'92s common for a text to simply end without a period (the send action acting as the full stop). When commas appear, they sometimes splice together what could be separate sentences, mirroring a breathless speaking style. 
\f1\b Ellipses (...)
\f0\b0  are a 
\f1\b signature
\f0\b0  punctuation mark in this corpus. The author loves to use \'93\'85\'94 to denote pauses, trailing thoughts, or implied unsaid feelings. We see ellipses both mid-sentence and as standalone messages. For example: 
\f1\b \'93Can I like...tell her?\'94
\f0\b0  uses an ellipsis to convey hesitation, and 
\f1\b \'93So..... This is where she will go violent tho\'94
\f0\b0  leads with a drawn-out pause (\'93So.....\'94) to build suspense or reluctance. Often multiple ellipses are strung together or extended beyond three dots, e.g. 
\f1\b \'93She's still...here....ughhhh\'94
\f0\b0  has an unusual four-dot sequence followed by another four-dot, emphasizing a long sigh or eye-roll before \'93ughhhh\'94. This heavy ellipsis use gives the text a 
\f2\i conversational rhythm
\f0\i0 , indicating when the author is pausing, unsure, or implying something.\
In contrast to the soft pause of ellipses, the author also uses 
\f1\b exclamation points
\f0\b0  and 
\f1\b question marks
\f0\b0  in repeated sequences for emotional effect. 
\f1\b Multiple exclamation points
\f0\b0  are very common, especially in affectionate or excited statements (e.g., 
\f1\b \'93We\'92re gonna fight if you keep calling my dreamgirl a hoe Casey !!!!\'94
\f0\b0  uses four exclamation marks to ensure the playful threat is read as hyperbole). Similarly, 
\f1\b \'93No!!!!! Gabeyyyyy\'94
\f0\b0  shows a dramatic \'93No\'94 with five exclamation marks and a stretched name, expressing mock despair in a joking context. Question marks get the same treatment when appropriate \'96 often the author will use 
\f1\b \'93?!\'94
\f0\b0  or 
\f1\b \'93?!?!\'94
\f0\b0  to convey incredulity or an excited question, as in 
\f1\b \'93Hahah how can you tell?!?!\'94
\f0\b0 . The mixing of \'93?\'94 and \'93!\'94 punctuations (interrobang style) shows the author\'92s combined surprise and question, effectively replacing a tone of voice. Single questions in casual contexts may even lack a question mark if the tone is understood (though this is less common).\

\f1\b Creative Spelling and Emphasis:
\f0\b0  Orthographically, the author is not afraid to bend spelling rules for effect. We\'92ve noted the deliberate elongation of words with repeated letters \'96 this is technically an orthographic choice to signal emphasis (e.g., 
\f2\i \'93sooo happy\'94
\f0\i0 , 
\f2\i \'93miss ur faaaace\'94
\f0\i0 ). They also occasionally use nonstandard spellings to represent accents or humorous pronunciation. For instance, writing 
\f1\b \'93ya\'94
\f0\b0  for 
\f2\i you
\f0\i0 , 
\f1\b \'93knooow\'94
