\f2\i \'93I love you so much and I want you to know\'85 nobody in my family could imagine you not going [with us]\'94
\f0\i0 . Even casual notes carry tenderness, as when he texts 
\f2\i \'93I miss you so much\'94
\f0\i0  on the same night. By contrast, platonic chats (with friends or family) lean on humor, updates, and light insults as bonding. For example, joking with a male friend, he uses exaggerated slang: 
\f2\i \'93you\'92ll have plenty of spank bank tendies\'94
\f0\i0  (a crass humorous remark) while helping investigate something. He teases friends in ways he wouldn\'92t his partner \'96 one friend exclaims 
\f2\i \'93LOL you DAWG\'94
\f0\i0  in response to his antics, highlighting how their banter includes rowdy, frat-boy slang. With romantic partners he 
\f1\b never
\f0\b0  uses such terms; instead of \'93dawg\'94 or \'93bro,\'94 he prefers 
\f2\i \'93love bug\'94
\f0\i0  or simply the partner\'92s name with endearment. Even mild profanity that appears in loving context is playful, not insulting \'96 e.g. calling his girlfriend\'92s cat 
\f2\i \'93Gabe would eat her for breakfast and then snuggle\'94
\f0\i0  followed by 
\f2\i \'93You're done for\'85 it will be a fun kidnapping\'94
\f0\i0  in a joking fantasy. With friends, profanity is more casual and often self-deprecating or sarcastic rather than loving. The lexical choice thus shifts from romantic affection (affectionate pronouns, pet names, \'93I love you\'94) to platonic camaraderie (slang, \'93lol,\'94 and mock-insults), aligning with the relationship type.\

\f1\b Emotion Words and Topics:
\f0\b0  Romantic texts revolve around personal feelings, future plans together, and mutual care. He openly discusses emotions \'96 
\f2\i \'93I want you to be happy and proud of me\'85 I\'92m sorry if I\'92ve done a bad job of that recently\'94
\f0\i0  he writes in a vulnerable moment. In platonic contexts, especially with male friends, deep emotional vocabulary is rarer; conversations skew to external topics (music, drugs, plans) or shared humor. For example, he engages in philosophical debate with a friend about cynicism and privilege, using intellectual and vulgar terms rather than emotional pleas: 
\f2\i \'93So fuck all about being high and cynical\'85if you\'92re following the only true god...instinct\'94
\f0\i0 . Even when he does talk about personal struggles with friends, he remains somewhat detached or jokey (calling himself 
\f2\i \'93scum\'94
\f0\i0  and life 
\f2\i \'93a parody\'94
\f0\i0 ). In sum, the author\'92s 
\f1\b lexical choices adapt
\f0\b0  to audience: emotive and loving for a partner, versus irreverent or matter-of-fact for friends.\

\f1\b Pronoun & Form Changes:
\f0\b0  Notably, he shifts the shorthand for \'93you\'94 depending on context (and over time). In intimate messages, especially early on, he occasionally uses the ultra-casual 
\f2\i \'93u\'94
\f0\i0  (e.g. 
\f2\i \'93I notice things u say. Everything you say! Don\'92t ever change\'94
\f0\i0  from 2015) when excited, but more often spells it out fully in heartfelt statements (
\f2\i \'93I love you so so much\'94
\f0\i0 ). With friends, the shorthand \'93u\'94 remains common in quick inquiries or directives (
\f2\i \'93U around?\'94
\f0\i0 , 
\f2\i \'93Should we go to sheetz or come to u\'94
\f0\i0 ), reflecting a faster, transactional tone. Over the years, as his texting matured, \'93u\'94 appears less with his partner (by 2023 nearly all 
\f1\b \'93you\'94
\f0\b0  in serious contexts) while it still pops up in casual friend exchanges. Similarly, the capital \'93I\'94 is often downcased to \'93i\'94 in both contexts to convey informality, but he\'92s somewhat more likely to capitalize \'93I\'94 in serious or apologetic messages to his girlfriend (perhaps to add gravity). This subtle morphosyntactic adaptation \'96 toggling between textese and standard forms \'96 shows him calibrating the 
\f1\b register
\f0\b0  based on the relationship and the message\'92s weight.\

\f1\b Conversation Cadence:
\f0\b0  In romantic chats, the cadence is rapid and continuous throughout the day, with many back-and-forth bursts especially during emotional discussions. He\'92ll send multiple short messages in a row to his partner, mimicking a spoken stream (\'93I love you\'85\'94, followed seconds later by \'93I miss u\'94, and then a practical note). With platonic friends, the exchanges are often more sporadic and context-driven (setting up plans, sharing a joke/meme). He might have intense bursty exchanges with close friends (especially if they\'92re collaborating on something fun, as on 2020-03-23 when he and a friend excitedly trade rapid messages about investigating a camgirl, with each sending many one-liners and media in succession). But generally, continuous daylong dialogue is reserved for his romantic partner. Friends get pings as needed \'96 
\f2\i \'93U around\'94
\f0\i0 , 
\f2\i \'93Need a b\'94
\f0\i0  (probably a \'93bowl\'94 of something) \'96 and the conversations often have a specific purpose or end after a few exchanges. This difference in cadence underscores that with romantic partners the 
