\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 Secure vs. Volatile Emotional Moments\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf0 Calm vs. Agitated Tone:
\f0\b0  When the relationship atmosphere is secure or emotions are neutral, the author\'92s style is relaxed and cooperative. In calm moments he often uses polite or loving language, even when making requests \'96 for example, a routine coordination text to his partner: 
\f2\i \'93I love you, have fun. Try to relax\'94
\f0\i0  shows supportive brevity with a caring undertone, punctuated by an affectionate assurance. His sentences in secure times are straightforward and often end with no period or a gentle emoji, indicating an easygoing flow. However, in 
\f2\i volatile emotional moments
\f0\i0  \'96 times of conflict, anxiety, or urgency \'96 his tone and mechanics shift dramatically. He becomes more abrupt, and the messages reflect stress through punctuation and brevity. For instance, during a tense exchange he starts a message with 
\f2\i \'93Please stop!\'94
\f0\i0  and follows with, 
\f2\i \'93I don\'92t need you to remind me to worry about shit\'85not in front of her\'94
\f0\i0 , using an exclamation and sharp wording that conveys frustration. The contrast is stark: the calm \'93try to relax\'94 versus the agitated \'93Please stop!\'94 illustrates how his diction hardens under duress.\

\f1\b Punctuation as Emotional Gauge:
\f0\b0  The author 
\f1\b stacks punctuation
\f0\b0  and uses unconventional formatting far more in volatile moments. When confused, upset, or demanding answers, he piles question marks or exclamation points, which is rare in secure exchanges. In one argument with his girlfriend, he leads a message with 
\f2\i \'93???\'94
\f0\i0  to convey bewilderment and urgency: 
\f2\i \'93??? you had told me that you would be able to come pick me up\'94
\f0\i0 . This triple-\'93?\'94 is a clear marker of his urgent need for explanation. In normal circumstances, he would pose a question with a single \'93?\'94 or often just implicit tone, but here the 
\f1\b multiple question marks
\f0\b0  signal emotional volatility. Similarly, exclamation points multiply when he\'92s shouting or passionate. A playful example is 
\f2\i \'93No!!!!! Gabeyyyyy\'94
\f0\i0  (five exclamation marks) when excitedly talking about a cat \'96 though playful, it shows heightened emotion. In conflict, exclamations also appear but with anger: e.g. 
\f2\i \'93Leave now\'94
\f0\i0  he snaps during a minor spat, or 
\f2\i \'93Nice attitude.\'94
\f0\i0  (sarcastic tone) in another fight, which, while a declarative statement, follows an exclamatory emotional context. Ellipses and abrupt line breaks emerge in volatile moments as well \'96 he sometimes sends an incomplete thought or uses \'93\'85\'94 to indicate a pause or choked feeling. For instance, mid-argument he might send a one-liner like \'93What?\'94 or trail off (\'93I\'92m not sure how you get to say that when I\'85\'94) before hitting send, reflecting a halting, upset cadence. 
\f1\b In contrast, during secure moments
\f0\b0  his messages don\'92t rely on such heavy punctuation for tone; a content line might simply end without a period or with a single emoji. The emotional punctuation (!!!, ???, ?!) is thus a reliable tell for his heightened emotional state.\

\f1\b Sentence Structure & Length:
\f0\b0  Volatility also affects his syntax. In secure or happy exchanges, he often writes in fragments or short sentences 
\f2\i out of habit
\f0\i0 , but these fragments flow logically and can even be combined in one message. For example, on an ordinary day he might write a multi-clause text about plans in one go. However, under stress he breaks his thoughts into multiple rapid-fire messages and sometimes 
\f1\b omits subjects or verbs
\f0\b0 , reflecting rushed speech. In one fight, he sends a series of fragmented messages within seconds: 
\f2\i \'93I\'92m not mad at you but I\'92m srs that your vibe is\'85full of anxiety\'94
\f0\i0 , followed immediately by 
\f2\i \'93Nice attitude. I\'92m just telling you I don\'92t need oversight right now\'94
\f0\i0 . These could grammatically be one combined statement, but he splits them, each hitting a tone \'96 one apologetic, one annoyed. The 
\f1\b cadence quickens and statements shorten
\f0\b0  when he\'92s volatile: e.g. 
\f2\i \'93I\'92m not!\'94
\f0\i0  he interjects defensively in response to a charge. By contrast, in secure moments he\'92s capable of longer, more composed sentences (especially when reflecting or storytelling to his partner), stringing clauses with \'93and\'94 or \'93but.\'94 The volatility induces a staccato style \'96 one thought per message \'96 as if each text is a heated breath.\

\f1\b Vocabulary and Cursing:
\f0\b0  Emotional security vs. volatility also shows in word choice. In secure mode, he uses profanity mostly in jest or emphasis (e.g., calling something 
\f2\i \'93so fucking easy\'94
\f0\i0  when excitedly confident, or tossing a casual 
\f2\i \'93lol that\'92s the fucking worst\'94
\f0\i0  in dark humor with family). These are intensifiers but not directed 
\f2\i at
\f0\i0  someone. In volatile moments, profanity can turn pointed or reflect genuine anger. For instance, in a conflict he tells his girlfriend 
\f2\i \'93your vibe is fucking so full of anxiety\'94
\f0\i0  \'96 here 
\f2\i \'93fucking\'94
\f0\i0  is a negative intensifier aimed at her demeanor, something he\'92d avoid when calm. During fights he might also use harsh phrases like 
\f2\i \'93How FUCKING TERRIBLE you are making me look\'94
\f0\i0  (an example from the Phase 1 report) to express feeling wronged. Outside of conflict, that level of direct profanity toward the other person is absent \'96 he\'92s affectionate or at worst teasing. We also see that in volatility he sometimes lapses into all-caps for shouted words (e.g. \'93NOT\'94 or \'93NEED\'94 for emphasis in arguments). In secure times, all-caps are used playfully (like 
\f2\i \'93DRIVE SAFE\'94
\f0\i0  as a loving command) or not at all. The 
\f1\b emotional temperature
\f0\b0  clearly governs his register: a calm heart yields gentle or joking words; a riled mind yields sharpened language and structure.\

\f1\b Emotional Reassurance Patterns:
\f0\b0  Interestingly, after volatile spikes, his style often shifts into a 
\f2\i remorseful or reassuring mode
\f0\i0 , which is another aspect of adaptation. Once a fight cools, he floods his partner with apologies and comforting words in a very 
\f1\b formulaic, earnest
\f0\b0  style. He\'92ll repeat phrases like 
\f2\i \'93I\'92m sorry\'94
\f0\i0 , 
\f2\i \'93I love you\'94
\f0\i0 , and 
\f2\i \'93I promise\'94
\f0\i0  multiple times, sometimes in succession. For example, after a tense night he writes, 
\f2\i \'93I love you so much, I want you to be happy\'85 I\'92m sorry if I\'92ve done a bad job of that recently\'94
\f0\i0 , followed by assurances of her uniqueness: 
\f2\i \'93You\'92re the only one\'85\'94
\f0\i0  (text cut off but clearly praising her) right after. The language here is soft, full of 
\f1\b first-person responsibility
\f0\b0  (\'93I\'92m sorry, I want you to be proud\'94) and second-person focus (\'93you be happy, you\'92re the only one\'85\'94). These reassurance messages often forego slang and are written with proper capitalization and spelling \'96 a notable switch into a more formal tone, likely to underscore sincerity. This pattern doesn\'92t occur in platonic volatile moments (with friends, arguments are extremely rare or brief), but it\'92s a cycle in his romantic communication: volatility triggers clipped, intense messages, which then give way to verbose apologies and affirmations once he regains a secure footing.\
